I suggest to use `java.util.Set` (if allowed) to eliminate the need for checking for duplicates since sets in Java do not allow duplicate values to be inserted. So, a set-based solution will look like this:

```
public static void main(String[] args) {
	Integer[][] card = new Integer[5][5];
	Set&lt;Integer&gt; row = null;

	int seed = 1;
	for (int i = 0; i &lt; card.length; i++) {
		row = new LinkedHashSet&lt;&gt;();
		if (i != 0) {
			seed +=15;
		}
		while (row.size() &lt; card[0].length) {
			row.add((int)(Math.random() * 14)+seed);
		}
		card[i] = (Integer[])row.toArray(Integer[]::new);
		System.out.println(row);
	}
}
```
This will result in an output that will look something like this:
```
[1, 4, 14, 8, 2]
[26, 23, 28, 20, 17]
[34, 40, 36, 41, 43]
[46, 48, 58, 49, 51]
[66, 72, 63, 64, 71]
```
The beauty of ***LinkedHashSet*** is that:

 1. It ***prevents duplicate values*** to be inserted
 2. ***Preserves the insertion order***; acting like an array.

Of course, I assume that duplicate values are only to be prevented in a single row and that a duplicate value could exist in another row. Obviously, if each of the values must be unique, you would need to allow for your randomization function to provide values from 1 up to the number of cells in the grid AND you will generate all the values (in this case 25 values first, and then you will loop thru the set and add the values to each cell after the set is generated.

---

