```
public class BingoBoard2 {

	public static void main(String[] args) {
		int GRID_SIZE = 5;
		int[][] card = new int[GRID_SIZE][GRID_SIZE];
		int seed = 1;
		for (int col = 0; col &lt; GRID_SIZE; col++) {
			if (col != 0) {
				seed += 15;
			}
			for (int row = 0; row &lt; GRID_SIZE; row++ ) {
				int value = -1;
				do {
					value = (int) (Math.random() * 14) + seed;
				} while (valueInArray(card, col, row, value));
				card[row][col] = value;					
			}
		}

		StringBuilder buff = new StringBuilder();
		Arrays.stream(card).forEach((i) -&gt; {
			buff.append(&quot;[&quot;);
			Arrays.stream(i).forEach((j) -&gt; buff.append(j + &quot; &quot;));
			buff.replace(buff.toString().lastIndexOf(&quot; &quot;), buff.length(),  &quot;&quot;);
			buff.append(&quot;]\n&quot;);
		});
		
		System.out.print(buff.toString().replaceAll(&quot; &quot;, &quot;, &quot;));
	}
	
	private static boolean valueInArray(int[][] arr, int col, int maxIndex, int value) {

		for (int row = 0; row &lt; maxIndex; row++) {
			if (arr[row][col] == value) {
				return true;
			}
		}
		return false;
	}
}
```
This latest solution

 1. Doesn&#39;t use `Set` or `LinkedHashSet`
 2. Doesn&#39;t transpose the 2D array
 3. Doesn&#39;t insert duplicate values into the array.

The check for duplicate simply checks the current column values in the range of index 0 up to the current index. Basically, it checks all previous inserts in the current column. Since the randomizer generates unique values for each column (based on BINGO), there is no need to check for duplicates outside the current column. So, per column, ***there will be approximately 4! checks per column*** (*5 * 4!* per board - or 50 checks if my math is correct).

